objects.name: Dementia disease
objects.description:
Dementia is a term used to describe a group of symptoms that affect memory, thinking, and social abilities severely enough to interfere with daily functioning. It is not a specific disease but a collection of symptoms caused by various underlying conditions.

The brain is primarily affected in cases of dementia. In particular, various regions of the brain involved in cognitive and behavioral functions may be affected, such as the hippocampus, which plays a crucial role in memory formation and recall. The cerebral cortex, which is responsible for language, perception, and reasoning, may also be affected. Additionally, the frontal lobes, which control decision-making and social behavior, can be impacted in some forms of dementia.

Other areas of the brain that may be involved include the amygdala, which is responsible for emotional processing, and the basal ganglia, which are involved in motor control and coordination.

Overall, dementia is a complex condition that can impact different areas of the brain depending on the underlying cause, which can vary from person to person.

objects.name: Epicrises
objects.description:
Epicrisis is a document that summarizes a patient's medical history, diagnosis, treatment, and outcome, typically prepared by a hospital or healthcare provider upon discharge from a hospital or completion of a course of treatment.
Epicrisis serves as an important record of a patient's medical care and can be used to provide information to other healthcare providers involved in the patient's care. It may also be used for billing and insurance purposes.
The diagnosis of dementia may also be recorded in other parts of a patient's medical records, such as progress notes, lab reports, imaging studies, and other clinical documents. These records are typically maintained by the healthcare provider or healthcare organization and are subject to applicable laws and regulations regarding confidentiality, privacy, and security.

Including: 
Surname, name, patronymic, date of birth, how many full years, place of residence.
The detailed proved diagnosis.
Complaints of the patient.
Anamnesis of the disease.
The patients initial condition.
Laboratory and other studies.
Consultations of specialists.

objects.name: Family & Friends
objects.description:
Role of Family in Dementia Treatment

Emotional support: Family members play a vital role in providing emotional support to the person with dementia. They can help the person feel loved, valued, and secure, which can have a positive impact on their emotional well-being and overall quality of life.

Practical assistance: Family members can assist with daily tasks such as personal care, meal preparation, and medication management. This support can help the person with dementia maintain their independence and dignity for as long as possible.

Monitoring symptoms and treatment: Family members can help monitor the person's symptoms and response to treatment, providing valuable information to healthcare professionals. This can help ensure that the person receives appropriate care and support throughout the course of their illness.

Advocacy: Family members can advocate for the person with dementia, ensuring that their needs and preferences are considered in care planning and decision-making processes.

Social engagement: Family members can help the person with dementia maintain social connections and engage in meaningful activities, which can contribute to their overall well-being and quality of life.

Role of Experts in Dementia Treatment

Diagnosis and assessment: Healthcare professionals, such as neurologists, geriatricians, and psychiatrists, play a crucial role in diagnosing dementia and assessing its severity. They can also help identify any underlying medical conditions that may be contributing to the person's symptoms.

Medical treatment: Experts can prescribe medications to help manage symptoms of dementia, such as memory loss, agitation, and sleep disturbances. They can also monitor the person's response to treatment and make adjustments as needed.

Non-pharmacological interventions: Healthcare professionals, such as occupational therapists, speech therapists, and psychologists, can provide non-pharmacological interventions to help improve the person's cognitive function, communication skills, and overall quality of life.

Care planning and coordination: Experts can help develop a comprehensive care plan that addresses the person's medical, psychological, and social needs. They can also coordinate care among various healthcare providers and support services, ensuring that the person receives appropriate and timely care.

Education and support: Healthcare professionals can provide education and support to family members and caregivers, helping them understand the nature of dementia and how to best care for the person with the condition.

Conclusion

The role of family and experts in dementia treatment is essential in providing comprehensive care and support to the person with dementia. Family members can offer emotional support, practical assistance, and advocacy, while experts can provide medical treatment, non-pharmacological interventions, and care coordination. By working together, family members and experts can help improve the quality of life for the person with dementia and support them throughout the course of their illness.

objects.name: Initial cognitive test
objects.description:
An initial cognitive test by a General Practitioner (GP) typically involves a brief assessment of a patient's cognitive function, memory, attention, and language skills. This is done to identify any potential cognitive impairments or decline, such as dementia or Alzheimer's disease. The GP may use various screening tools and tests, such as:

Mini-Mental State Examination (MMSE): A widely used test that assesses cognitive function by asking the patient to perform tasks related to orientation, memory, attention, and language.

Montreal Cognitive Assessment (MoCA): A more comprehensive test that evaluates various cognitive domains, including memory, attention, language, and executive functions.

Clock Drawing Test: A simple test where the patient is asked to draw a clock with the hands showing a specific time. This test assesses visual-spatial and executive functioning.

Verbal Fluency Test: The patient is asked to name as many words as possible within a certain category (e.g., animals) or starting with a specific letter within a given time. This test evaluates language and executive functions.

Memory tests: The GP may ask the patient to remember and later recall a list of words or a short story to assess their memory function.

Attention tests: The patient may be asked to perform tasks that require sustained attention, such as counting backward from 100 by sevens or reciting the months of the year in reverse order.

General questions about daily functioning: The GP may ask the patient about their ability to perform daily tasks, such as managing finances, cooking, or taking medications, to assess their overall cognitive function.

Based on the results of these tests and the patient's medical history, the GP may refer the patient to a specialist, such as a neurologist or geriatrician, for further evaluation and management of cognitive issues.

objects.name: MMSE Cognitiv test
objects.description:
The Mini-Mental State Examination (MMSE) is a commonly used test to assess cognitive function in older adults. It is a brief, standardized, and easy-to-administer screening tool that assesses various cognitive domains such as orientation, attention, memory, language, and visual-spatial skills.

The MMSE test includes a series of questions and tasks that require the individual to perform simple mental tasks such as counting backwards from 100 by sevens, recalling a list of words, and identifying the current date and location. The test takes about 10-15 minutes to administer and yields a score ranging from 0 to 30, with a higher score indicating better cognitive function.

The MMSE test is widely used in clinical settings to screen for cognitive impairment and to monitor changes in cognitive function over time. However, it is important to note that the MMSE is a screening tool and should not be used as a diagnostic tool on its own. It is recommended to be used in conjunction with other clinical and neuropsychological assessments to establish a comprehensive understanding of an individual's cognitive abilities.
